Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back to CSK's reply with the bat. Out walk the CSK openers - Ayush Mhatre and Shaik Rasheed. Royal Challengers Bengaluru players now spread out across the field. Remember, there's no Hazlewood for RCB tonight. And surprisingly, they are going with spin first up. Krunal Pandya has been handed over the new ball and will open the attack for the home side. Mhatre to face the first ball. Here we go...
... THE RUN CHASE ...

With all the momentum springing back in RCB's favor in those last couple of overs, they have put on a total that CSK hasn't chased in a long, long time. In fact, the men in yellow have not chased anything above 180 since last few years now. With one of the worst batting averages in the Powerplay this season, averaging just 7.91 in the field restrictions, they will need a strong start from the openers. But they will be up against a quality RCB bowling unit. Stay tuned as the run chase is up next shortly.

Royal Challengers Bengaluru's Jacob Bethell, is up for a chat. On Romario Shepherd's knock, Bethell says that it was incredible to watch. Adds that he doesn't think that he middled all his shots but it didn't seem like that. On his opening partnership with Virat Kohli, Jacob says that the duo made sure that it kept hitting everything down the ground. Informs that the feedback from Virat Kohli on the pitch was that there was not much bounce and to try and get on top of the new ball. On batting against the new ball, JB says that there wasn't much swing early on and that made batting easier. Adds that he loved hitting the ball through the covers. On the experience to be playing alongside Kohli, Jacob Bethell says that it was pretty cool to be with him in Delhi and even more so tonight, as he got to spend some more time in the middle with the legend. On RCB's score, Bethell says that the team wanted 210, so they are happy that they got that. Informs that there was some spin in the middle overs, so expects RCB's spinners to extract spin as well. Feels that the cameo from Romario Shepherd has given Bengaluru plenty of momentum.

However, what followed next was the muscle power of Romario Shepherd. He provided the much-needed propulsion for RCB, with those finishing touches, taking on Khaleel Ahmed to the cleaners, smashing 33 off that penultimate over, which was also the costliest over this season so far by any bowler. All of a sudden, from being 159/4 at the beginning of the penultimate over, RCB sprang to 200-plus courtesy of a 14-ball blinder 50 from Shepherd, which included 6 sixes and four boundaries.

The incoming batters did try to sustain that momentum, but Kohli's departure brought in a bit of a slowdown, however, RCB were still marching along with a run rate in touching distance of 10s. Introduced early, Pathirana struck off in his first over, and it seemed to be his night as he chipped in with crucial wickets of Padikkal and Patidar. Sooner, RCB slipped from 97/0 to 157/5.

CSK bowlers were not consistent with their lines and lengths and took a tour all around the park as RCB were cruising like a runaway train. Alarm bells were already ringing for CSK, as their best bowler, Khaleel Ahmed, was made to travel as well. Almost all bowlers were taken to the cleaners, but Jadeja bowled a couple of quiet overs, and then Pathirana chipped in with the first breakthrough. Virat Kohli too, got out sooner, but not before smashing 7th fifty of this season, and marking his fifth fifty-plus score in the last six innings.

RCB got off to a very positive start for RCB as both Virat Kohli and Jacob Bethell treated with some exquisite shots that were not only eye-pleasing, but helped the home side to form a solid foundation right away. Add to CSK's woes, Bethell was dropped on 17 by Pathirana and survived a couple of close chances as well. As if luck was on his side tonight. With a flurry of boundaries, RCB bossed the Powerplay, posting 71/0 on the board.

MAYDAY, MAYDAY, MAYDAY! That's what CSK would have screamed out of their lungs after witnessing an absolute carnage in the last two overs. RCB were nowhere in the vicinity of that 200-run mark, but this cameo from Romario Shepherd has just flipped the game 180 degrees. A blinder of a finish, and Tim David, the other brute hitter, on the other end, was just made to be a spectator. Shepherd sprints into the dugout, and is welcomed by the joyous RCB players. Feel for the CSK bowlers, though. They applied the brakes in the mid overs, only to witness something out of the book in the death overs.

SIX! 14-BALL 50 FOR SHEPHERD! A new hero for the Royal Challengers Bengaluru. A length ball, outside off, change in pace, but the West Indian reads that. Gives himself room to the leg side and sends it sailing over long off! Shepherd swings his bat to the RCB dugout, getting his name in the record books. The fastest fifty in the IPL belongs to Yashasvi Jaiswal in 13 balls and this is now the second fastest fifty! 54 runs come in the last 2 overs, with Shepherd making 52 of those! RCB FINISH ON 213/5!

Commentary.Commentary: STRATEGIC TIMEOUT. This one called by the Royal Challengers Bengaluru. This has been a trend this season, with the batting side opting to call for the timeout around the 13th or the 14th over, treating the last 5-6 overs like another Powerplay. It has been a tough outing for Chennai Super Kings so far, with only 6 overs out of 13 going in single digits. Nearly everyone has travelled, with a slight exception in Anshul Kamboj and Ravindra Jadeja. Of course, Pathirana has bowled just 1 over. With a big batting lineup, the hosts seem poised to get to 220, but given that Pathirana has taken a wicket in his opening over, could tonight be the night where his fortunes change? Also, with two new batters in the middle, there could be a slight loss in momentum for the home side.

Commentary.Commentary: The umpires make their way out to the middle. The Chennai team is done with its last-minute pep talk and spreads out onto the field. And now, to the loud cheers of the Chinnaswamy crowd, Virat Kohli strides out to the middle, followed by the much-acclaimed future of English cricket - Jacob Bethell. As usual, it will be the left-arm seam of Khaleel Ahmed to start things off, against the left-handed Bethell. Here we go...

The captain of RCB, Rajat Patidar, says that they would have fielded as well, but reckons that the pitch won't change much. Adds that everyone is in a good frame of mind. Further mentions that everyone has performed well and they will try their best in the remaining games. Informs that Lungi Ngidi comes in for Josh Hazlewood.

The captain of CSK, MS Dhoni, says that they want to make the most out of the last four remaining games and want to win games because that always helps. Adds that they will try to look into next year on which individual will fit into what role. On the surface, he says it looks a bit tacky as it has been under covers for most of the time, and also says it is a venue where scoring runs a bit easier. Mentions it is a high-scoring venue and after the initial start, he feels it will be good to bat on. Shares that it is important to express and play to the strengths, make a plan and look to execute. States that they will look how the wicket behaves and will take it forward. Concludes by saying they are going unchanged.

Impact Player options for RCB - Suyash Sharma, Rasikh Salam, Manoj Bhandage, Liam Livingstone, Swapnil Singh.

Royal Challengers Bengaluru (Playing XI) - Virat Kohli, Jacob Bethell, Devdutt Padikkal (In for Suyash Sharma), Rajat Patidar (C), Romario Shepherd, Jitesh Sharma (WK), Tim David, Krunal Pandya, Bhuvneshwar Kumar, Lungi Ngidi (In for Josh Hazlewood), Yash Dayal.
TOSS - Chennai Super Kings win the coin flip and they will BOWL first

PITCH REPORT - Ian Bishop is accompanied by Shane Watson for the pitch analysis. Ian Bishop first shares a good news that the conditions overhead are clear, but also adds that there was a lot of rain over the past few days. Says that the pitch is at dead-center with equidistant dimensions of 64 meters at the squares, while the straight hit is 73 meters. Points that pitch number 7 has seen a couple of varying scores. Shane Watson joins him and says the pitch looks really nice and observes that it is quite dry with not much grass covering. Reckons that there won't be much tennis-ball bounce on it, and the ball might come a bit easier on the bat, and opines that the batters will be able to trust the bounce. Says the team batting first must put a big total on the board as it looks like a really good surface.

Right then, two teams playing for two different agendas but with the level of play being so high in IPL, no team is guaranteed a win. Also, there is some threat of rain, but let's hope that it stays away. Stay tuned as the toss and team sheets will be up in a bit.

It has been a forgetful season for CSK, and with them being out of the playoffs race, they might just be able to let loose and derail RCB's progress, just like RCB halted their progress to the playoffs last season in a thrilling fashion. CSK have had a few bright spots as well and they will take the positive signs that the youngsters have shown great promise whenever given a chance, but the big names will be hoping to finish the season on a high.

RCB have broken the duck at home after a bit of an early hiatus from a home win this season, they are now well and truly inside the top four. The team has really started to click and they will be hoping for another win to really solidify their claim for a playoffs berth.

Hello and welcome to the M. Chinnaswamy Stadium in Bengaluru where home side Royal Challengers Bengaluru go up against Chennai Super Kings in take 2 of the southern derby of IPL 2025. RCB reigned victorious at the Chepauk after an eternity but CSK will be out for revenge. It is always an intriguing contest when these two sides face each other and this one should be the same.
... MATCH DAY ...

Cricket's battlefield shifts to the electric Chinnaswamy Stadium, where two IPL titans prepare for a collision that promises fireworks beyond the scoreboard. As Royal Challengers Bengaluru host Chennai Super Kings in Match 52, we're set for another thrilling chapter in the Virat Kohli-MS Dhoni saga, a rivalry that continues to captivate cricket lovers everywhere. When these giants first clashed this season, both teams were riding the high of opening victories. Since then? It's been a tale of dramatically different journeys. RCB stunned Chennai at their fortress Chepauk, but what followed was a frustrating pattern of inconsistency – win, loss, win, loss – a rollercoaster that kept them from building momentum despite flashes of brilliance. But just when critics wondered if they'd ever find consistency, RCB has exploded with three consecutive victories, propelling them into serious playoff contention with a real shot at the coveted top-two finish. Their dominant run now has them perched in the upper echelons of the table, showcasing the kind of form that makes opposition teams nervous. Virat Kohli has been the batting linchpin, crafting six masterful half-centuries and standing tall as the only RCB batter to cross the 400-run milestone. His consistency has him rubbing shoulders with the season's elite run-scorers. The numbers tell a revealing story – beyond Kohli, Phil Salt and Devdutt Padikkal haven't even reached 300 runs, yet RCB keeps winning. Their recipe? A top-order that absorbs pressure, Tim David's brute finishing blows, and Krunal Pandya's clutch all-round performances that repeatedly tip the scales. But RCB's true transformation this season lies in their bowling attack. The international pace duo of Bhuvneshwar Kumar and Josh Hazlewood has intimidated the batting orders, helping claim the second-most powerplay wickets in the tournament. Hazlewood's brilliance has earned him the prestigious Purple Cap. When batters dare to breathe easier against pace, the spin tandem of Krunal and Suyash Sharma springs the trap, creating a bowling unit with seemingly no weak links to exploit. Across the field, Chennai Super Kings find themselves in unfamiliar and uncomfortable territory. With a dismal record of eight defeats and just a couple of wins, they're one of just two teams already mathematically eliminated from playoff contention, marking only the second time in IPL history they've missed consecutive playoffs. Their maximum possible points tally of 12 falls well short of the qualification threshold, making this one of the earliest exits since Pune Warriors India's 2013 campaign. CSK's struggles begin in the powerplay, where they average a tournament-worst 7.91 runs while losing more wickets than any rival – a fatal combination that has repeatedly extinguished momentum before it could build. The batting unit has lacked both consistency and intent, with even MS Dhoni's usually reliable finishing touches failing to spark conviction. Yet even in this challenging season, CSK shows glimpses of their strategic vision. Young talents Shaik Rasheed and Ayush Mhatre are getting valuable exposure, while Dewald Brevis has brought much-needed boundary-clearing explosiveness. The bowling offers some consolation as Khaleel Ahmed strikes consistently with the new ball, while Noor Ahmad's wizardry has him among the tournament's top five wicket-takers. However, it's important to finish and bowl well in the death overs, which isn't coming for them. Their reliance on Matheesha Pathirana for the death bowling has proved too costly as the Sri Lankan slingy seamer has leaked runs at a worrisome economy rate. This is also one of the many reasons why they have lost games while doing both, defending and chasing. What makes this contest particularly intriguing is RCB's puzzling home record, with just one win against four losses at the usually formidable Chinnaswamy Stadium. Can they overcome this strange home disadvantage against a wounded CSK side with nothing to lose but pride? When these cricket royalties clash under Bengaluru's lights, expect nothing less than a spectacle where a vision for the future meets determination. Will RCB continue their march toward glory, or will Dhoni's men remind everyone why, even in defeat, champions never truly lose their roar? But, forecasts predict that this generational clash might get rain interruptions as the weather in Bengaluru has been a bit overcast over a couple of days. But, hopes are of a complete game of cricket. Brace yourselves, as the Garden City braces for cricket theater at its finest!

Equation: Chennai Super Kings need 214 runs in 120 balls at 10.7 rpo
